benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/accounts/{accountId}/overdue - Retrieve overdue state for account

covered: Valid Request: Successful retrieval for a valid account is covered (TC01).
Empty/No-data Response: Handling of an account with no overdue state is covered (TC02) and empty DB behavior is covered (TC13).
Error Responses (400/404): Malformed UUID, missing/unsupported accountId, and non-existent account are covered (TC03, TC04, TC05, TC06, TC16).
Authorization (basic): Missing and invalid auth token cases are covered (TC07, TC08) returning 401.
Query Parameters: Extra/ignored query parameter behavior is covered (TC12).
Server/Dependency Errors: Server error, backend unavailable, and degraded dependency scenarios covered (TC09, TC17).
Security Input Validation: Injection and XSS attempts in accountId are tested (TC10, TC11).
Performance & Concurrency: Single-request performance and concurrent retrievals are covered (TC14, TC15).
Large Payload & Recovery: Large overdue history handling and transient network retry behavior are present (TC18, TC19).
Backward compatibility / Schema stability: Response structure/required fields checks are included (TC20) and JSON schema validation is asserted in success cases.
gaps: Pagination: No tests exist for pagination. (Note: endpoint appears to be single-resource; confirm whether pagination is applicable.)
Rate Limiting / Throttling: No tests for rate limiting or behavior under request bursts (429 handling).
Caching Behavior: No tests for caching headers (ETag, Last-Modified, Cache-Control) or conditional GET / 304 responses.
Authorization scope/permission checks (403): Tests cover 401 but not 403 or token-without-permission scenarios.
Response header validation: Content negotiation and other headers (e.g., Content-Length, Cache headers) are not validated beyond Content-Type.
Schema field-level negative testing: Tests assert schema match but do not validate missing/invalid fields within OverdueState or inconsistent payloads from backend.
Consistency of error format: No assertions ensuring error responses follow a standard error envelope/structure (fields, codes, messages).
Pagination/performance for very large result sets: While large single payload is covered, there are no tests for multiple large responses or memory/streaming limits.
recommendations: Confirm whether pagination applies; if yes add pagination tests (page/limit, out-of-range pages, large dataset traversal). If not applicable, document explicitly in API contract.
Add rate-limiting tests: burst of requests to verify 429 responses and retry-after header behavior.
Add caching tests: verify ETag/Last-Modified headers, conditional GET (If-None-Match / If-Modified-Since) and 304 behavior, and Cache-Control directives.
Expand authorization tests to cover 403 scenarios: valid token without required scope/role, expired token, and role-based access control checks.
Validate response headers beyond Content-Type (Content-Length sanity, charset, caching headers) and content negotiation when Accept header differs.
Add negative schema tests: force backend to return incomplete/extra fields and assert API returns appropriate error or normalizes the response.
Define and assert a consistent error response format and add tests ensuring all error scenarios conform to it (400/401/403/404/500/503/504).
Add rate/soak tests for sustained high load and memory/leak detection for repeated large payload responses.
Document expected behavior for whitespace-trimmed accountId handling (TC16) and add tests for URL-encoded inputs and percent-encoding edge cases.
